Analysis of the Carpentries Instructor Training Post-Workshop Survey Data

Lead: Kari L. Jordan

This analysis of The Carpentries Instructor Training post-workshop survey serves to offer recommendations for changes to curriculum and assessment of The Carpentries instructor training program.

There were a total 573 trainees who completed this survey in between June 2016 and February 2018.

Feedback about the overall training event.

Respondents were asked to rate their level of agreement about the following:

  • Worth: The training was worth my time.
  • Recommend: I would recommend this training to a friend/colleague.
  • Material: The material preented matched the description of the training event.
  • LearnedSkills: I learned skills that I will be able to use in my teaching.
  • InformationReasonableTime: The amount of information covered was reasonable for alloted time.
  • AtmosphereWelcoming: The overall atmosphere was welcoming.

Trainees were asked to describe their experience with the following topics before the training, and their change in knowledge of these topics after the training. The topics are as follows:

  • Assessment: Formative vs.summative assessment
  • BackwardsDesign: Backwards design
  • Carpentries: What the Carpentries are and what they do
  • Cognition: Levels of cognition
  • CognitiveLoad: Cognitive load
  • Feedback: Giving effective feedback
  • Memory: How human memory works
  • Motiation: Motivation
  • Novice: What makes someone a novice or expert

  • Assessment: Formative vs.summative assessment

Change in confidence with Carpentries teaching practices

  • Teach using live coding
  • Set up a workshop website
  • Use a concept map for lesson planning
  • Write a multiple choice question with diagnostic power
  • Write effective learning objectives

Likely to Recommend

Trainees were asked how likely they are to recommend a Software and/or Data Carpentry workshop to a friend or colleague using the Net Promoter Score. The scoring for this question based on a 0 to 10 scale. Respondents scoring from 0 to 6 are labeled Detractors, and are believed to be less likely to recommend a workshop. Those who respond with a score of 9 to 10 are called Promoters, and are considered likely to recommend a workshop. Respondents between 7 and 8 are labeled Passives, and their behavior falls in the middle of Promoters and Detractors.
